                            <h1>
                            Encircled in the Arms of His Love
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p2" class="">Elder Neal A. Maxwell</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/neal-a-maxwell?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/neal-a-maxwell-10.jpg" alt="Neal A. Maxwell" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        <div class="kicker" id="">Perplexing things will still happen, but, like Nephi, we can still know that God loves us, a &hellip; fact which can and will sustain us through so much!</div>
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">22911_000_007</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p4" class="">In the churn of crises and the sinister swirl of global events, true disciples will maintain faith in a revealing, loving God and in His plan for redeeming His children, which plan is the <span class="emphasis">why</span> of <span class="emphasis">all</span> that God does! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/1.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 1:39</a>). Furthermore, God&rsquo;s character, as revealed to us, tells us that He has the cosmic capacity to ensure that He really is &ldquo;able&rdquo; to do His immense work (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/27.20-21?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 27:20&ndash;21</a>; <a href="http://scriptures.byu.edu/getscrip.php?ID=24960">Joseph Smith Translation, Isa. 29:22&ndash;23</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p5" class="">True disciples will also maintain faith in His atoning Son, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, and, by being &ldquo;converted unto the Lord&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/1.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 1:22</a>), will be steadily undergoing a happy and &ldquo;mighty change&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/5.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 5:2</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.12-14?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:12&ndash;14</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p6" class="">Actually, brothers and sisters, Jesus is already victorious in the greatest battle anyway: &ldquo;In the world ye shall have tribulation: but be of good cheer; <span class="emphasis">I have overcome the world</span>&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/16.33?lang=eng#32" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 16:33</a>; emphasis added). The Atonement was accomplished, bringing a universal <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2000/05/resurrection?lang=eng">resurrection</a> to billions and billions, lifting all from the grave&mdash;regardless of how and when we got there! Therefore, on a clear night, though we see stars of incomprehensible longevity, they are not immortal. But, thankfully, we are!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p7" class="">Likewise, &ldquo;true believers&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/4-ne/1.36?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">4 Ne. 1:36</a>) will maintain faith in the latter-day Restoration with its empowering visitations, its prophets and apostles, and its &ldquo;plain and precious&rdquo; scriptures (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/13.29?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 13:29</a>). The gospel&rsquo;s first principles surely fit the last days.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p8" class="">Ironically, as the restored Church comes &ldquo;out of obscurity,&rdquo; what seem to be stern challenges will actually disclose further the distinctiveness of the Church (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/1.30?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 1:30</a>). Nevertheless, matching our behavior more closely with our beliefs will bring relentless reminders about the ongoing duties of discipleship.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p9" class="">The restored gospel is buoyant, wide, and deep&mdash;beyond our comprehension. It edifies, whether concerning divine design in the universe or stressing the importance of personal chastity and fidelity. Only meek disciples can safely handle such a bold theology.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p10" class="">With scriptures to anchor and reassure us, we, too, can &ldquo;look unto God &hellip; and he will <span class="emphasis">console [us]</span> in [our] afflictions&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/3.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 3:1</a>; emphasis added).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p11" class="">We, too, can be <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;supported under trials and troubles of every kind, yea, &hellip; he will still deliver [us]&rdquo;</span> (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/36.3,27?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 36:3, 27</a>; emphasis added).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p12" class="">For the Lord has said: &ldquo;I will be in your midst&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/49.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 49:27</a>). &ldquo;I will lead you along&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/78.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 78:18</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p13" class="">Furthermore, God will give us priceless, personal assurances through the Holy Ghost (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/14.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 14:26</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/36.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 36:2</a>). Whether in tranquil or turbulent times, our best source of comfort is the Comforter.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p14" class="">Enoch wept over the wickedness in his time, and, at first, &ldquo;refuse[d] to be comforted&rdquo; (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/7.4,44?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 7:4, 44</a>). But then came revelations, successively showing Jesus redeeming the world, the latter-day Restoration, and the Second Coming. Enoch was told to &ldquo;lift up [his] heart, and be glad&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/7.44?lang=eng#43" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 7:44</a>). The doctrines and revelations can likewise lift us&mdash;even amid &ldquo;wars and rumours of wars&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/24.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 24:6</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/mark/13.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mark 13:7</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/12.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 12:2</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/morm/8.30?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Morm. 8:30</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/45.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 45:26</a>). Thus we need not grow weary in our minds (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/12.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 12:3</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/84.80?lang=eng#79" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 84:80</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p15" class="">Our discipleship need not be dried out by discouragement or the heat of the day, nor should dismaying, societal symptoms &ldquo;weigh [us] down&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/9.25?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 9:25</a>), including &ldquo;in-your-face,&rdquo; carnal confrontiveness (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/32.38?lang=eng#37" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 32:38</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p16" class="">We may shrink from some things in the current human scene, but Jesus did not shrink in Gethsemane nor on Calvary. Instead, He &ldquo;finished [His] preparations unto the children of men&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/19.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 19:19</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p17" class="">Regarding trials, including of our faith and patience, there are no exemptions&mdash;only variations (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/23.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 23:21</a>). These calisthenics are designed to increase our capacity for happiness and service. Yet the faithful will not be totally immune from the events on this planet. Thus the courageous attitudes of imperiled Shadrach, Meshach, and Abed-nego are worthy of emulation. They knew that God could rescue them. &ldquo;But if not,&rdquo; they vowed, they would still serve God anyway (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/dan/3.16-18?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Dan. 3:16&ndash;18</a>). Similarly, keeping the unfashionable but imperative first and seventh commandments can reflect the courage which three young women displayed anciently; they said no with their lives (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/abr/1.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Abr. 1:11</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p18" class="">Therefore, we can be troubled on every side, but nothing can really separate us from the love of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-cor/4.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Cor. 4:8</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/rom/8.35-39?lang=eng#34" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Rom. 8:35&ndash;39</a>); worldly anxieties are not part of being &ldquo;anxiously engaged&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/58.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 58:27</a>). Even so, as Peter urged, we can and should cast our cares upon the Lord, because He surely cares for us! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/5.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 5:7</a>). Oh, brothers and sisters, the awaiting emancipation of such trusting surrender!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p19" class="">As to remedying our personal mistakes, we face no hindering traffic jams on the road of repentance. It is a toll road, not a freeway, and applying Christ&rsquo;s Atonement will speed us along.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p20" class="">There may need to be plain-speaking Jethros in our lives to stretch us (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ex/18.14-24?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ex. 18:14&ndash;24</a>) or moments of stark realization, as with the original Twelve, who rightly concluded: &ldquo;Lord, to whom shall we go? thou hast the words of eternal life&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/6.68?lang=eng#67" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 6:68</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p21" class="">Besides, unless we are filled with resolve, what will we say to the heroes and heroines of Martin&rsquo;s Cove and the Sweetwater? That &ldquo;we admire you, but we are reluctant to wade through our own rivers of chilling adversity&rdquo;?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p22" class="">Brothers and sisters, by divine appointment, &ldquo;these are [our] days&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/7.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 7:9</a>), since &ldquo;all things must come to pass in their time&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/64.32?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 64:32</a>). Moreover, though we live in a failing world, we have not been sent here to fail.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p23" class="">Recall the new star that announced the birth at Bethlehem? It was in its precise orbit long before it so shone. We are likewise placed in human orbits to illuminate. Divine correlation functions not only in the cosmos but on this planet, too. After all, the Book of Mormon plates were not buried in Belgium, only to have Joseph Smith born centuries later in distant Bombay.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p24" class="">The raising up of that constellation of &ldquo;wise&rdquo; Founding Fathers to produce America&rsquo;s remarkable Constitution, whose rights and protection belong to &ldquo;every man,&rdquo; was not a random thing either (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/101.77-78,80?lang=eng#76" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 101:77&ndash;78, 80</a>). One historian called our Founding Fathers &ldquo;the most remarkable generation of public men in the history of the United States or perhaps of any other nation&rdquo; (Arthur M. Schlesinger, <span class="emphasis">The Birth of the Nation</span> [1968], 245). Another historian added, &ldquo;It would be invaluable if we could know what produced this burst of talent from a base of only two and a half million inhabitants&rdquo; (Barbara W. Tuchman, <span class="emphasis">The March of Folly: From Troy to Vietnam</span> [1984], 18).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p25" class="">Yet some still settle for an inconsistent or incapable god. Laman and Lemuel, for instance, were aware of ancient Israel&rsquo;s miraculous rescue from Pharaoh&rsquo;s mighty armies, but they murmured and were intimidated by a mere, local Laban. We can be so provincial and so self-concerned. God, who oversees the interlacings of galaxies, stars, and worlds, asks us to confess His hand in our personal lives, too (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/59.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 59:21</a>). Have we not been reassured about the fall of one sparrow and that the very hairs of our heads are numbered? (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/10.29-30?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 10:29&ndash;30</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/84.80?lang=eng#79" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 84:80</a>). God is in the details! Just as the Lord knows all of His vast creations, He also knows and loves each in any crowd&mdash;indeed, He knows and loves each and all of mankind! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:17</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p26" class="">Consider His tender salutations to <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/1998/04/moses-witness-of-jesus-christ?lang=eng">Moses</a>&mdash;&ldquo;I know thee by name, and thou hast also found grace in my sight&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ex/33.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ex. 33:12</a>)&mdash;and to Joseph: &ldquo;This is My Beloved Son. Hear Him!&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/js-h/1.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">JS&mdash;H 1:17</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p27" class="">No wonder King Benjamin pleads with us to believe that we do not comprehend all that God comprehends (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/4.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 4:9</a>). Ignoring the revelations about God&rsquo;s astounding capacity is like playing aimlessly and contentedly with wooden blocks featuring the letters of the alphabet, without realizing Shakespearean sonnets were created using that same alphabet.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p28" class="">Father Abraham &ldquo;staggered not&rdquo; at the divine promise of posterity, because he was &ldquo;fully persuaded that, what [God] had promised, he was able also to perform&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/rom/4.20-21?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Rom. 4:20&ndash;21</a>). May we be &ldquo;fully persuaded.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p29" class="">These words of Anselm are thus such good counsel: &ldquo;Believe in order to understand,&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;understand [in order to] believe&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">St. Anselm,</span> trans. Sidney Norton Deane [1903], 7).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p30" class="">Brothers and sisters, though living in a time of commotion, we can stand in holy places and not be moved (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/45.32?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 45:32</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/87.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 87:8</a>). Though living in a time of violence, we can have that inner peace that passeth understanding (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/philip/4.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Philip. 4:7</a>). Perplexing things will still happen, but, like Nephi, we can still know that God loves us, a felicitous and fundamental fact which can and will sustain us through so much! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:17</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p31" class="">How can we know that God is aware of us and loves us? He tells us by the scriptures&mdash;likewise, by our honestly counting the blessings and bestowals of His grace in our lives. Most of all, He tells us by the still, small voice of the Spirit! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/34.38?lang=eng#37" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 34:38</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/78.17-19?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 78:17&ndash;19</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p32" class="">The &ldquo;mighty change&rdquo; required by discipleship may seem roller-coaster like, as soaring revelations bring the gravity of humbling perspective. It was so with Moses, who &ldquo;fell unto the earth&rdquo; and exclaimed, &ldquo;Man is nothing, which thing I never had supposed&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/1.9-10?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 1:9&ndash;10</a>). Then came, however, the divine, reassuring disclosure: &ldquo;For behold, this is my work and my glory&mdash;to bring to pass the <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/immortality?lang=eng">immortality</a> and eternal life of man&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/1.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 1:39</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p33" class="">&ldquo;Mighty&rdquo; changing, however, is mighty hard work, a labor made more difficult by heeding the unflattering urges of the natural man. Too often our possibilities have been muted by the mundane. We are scarcely ready for the vaulting revelations. Imagine&mdash;a spirit portion of each of us is actually eternal and that we were with God in the beginning! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/93.29,33?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 93:29, 33</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p34" class="">Of course we cannot fully comprehend all this <span class="emphasis">right now!</span> Of course we cannot know the meaning of all things <span class="emphasis">right now.</span> But we can know, <span class="emphasis">right now,</span> that God knows us and loves us individually!</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p35" class="">But, brothers and sisters, what keeps us from knowing and loving Him more? Our reluctance to give away all our sins&mdash;thinking, instead, a down payment will do. Likewise, our reluctance to let our wills be swallowed up in His will&mdash;thinking, instead, that merely acknowledging His will is sufficient! (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/15.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 15:7</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p36" class="">The Prophet Joseph Smith declared that God, &ldquo;before [the earth] rolled into existence, &hellip; contemplated the whole of the events connected with the earth. &hellip; [God] knew &hellip; the depth of iniquity that would be connected with the human <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a>, their weakness and strength, &hellip; the situation of all nations and &hellip; their destiny, &hellip; and [He] has made ample provision [for mankind&rsquo;s] redemption&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Teachings of the Prophet Joseph Smith,</span> sel. Joseph Fielding Smith [1976], 220).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p37" class="">Part of God&rsquo;s &ldquo;ample provision&rdquo; consists of imperfect people like you and me, committed to shining and serving in our appointed orbits, knowing all the while that we are encircled &ldquo;in the arms of [His] love&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/6.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 6:20</a>).</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/2002/11/encircled-in-the-arms-of-his-love.p38" class="">In the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
